WEBVTT

00:03.150 --> 00:08.380


02:27.430 --> 02:29.190
Can't believe it. They're right on time.

02:29.310 --> 02:31.650
Let's get these boys to their party.

02:51.420 --> 02:53.960
Mama!

03:24.200 --> 03:26.910
<i>It's 10:48 on Fat Tuesday, Mardi Gras-</i>

03:26.990 --> 03:29.710
<i>Now let's go back in time to 1964-</i>

03:29.790 --> 03:32.710
<i>The Beach Boys on 105-3 FM,</i>

03:33.040 --> 03:35.460
<i>the heart of New Orleans-</i>

04:00.360 --> 04:03.360
Okay. Take it out wide.
Give the pig some room.

06:52.780 --> 06:56.580
My daughter's on that ferry.
Please. Please.

06:56.950 --> 06:59.120
Oh, God, my daughter!

08:04.100 --> 08:05.690
Do the other side?

09:02.660 --> 09:04.290
ATF New Orleans, Agent Donnelly.

09:04.670 --> 09:06.540
Listen, call New Orleans PD.

09:06.670 --> 09:08.960
I want all surveillance
from the Algiers dock.

09:09.090 --> 09:10.420
Then call City Transit.

09:10.550 --> 09:12.720
I want
the Crescent City Bridge surveillance,

09:12.840 --> 09:14.470
<i>westbound between 10:00 and 11:00-</i>

09:14.590 --> 09:15.630
All right, got it.

09:56.090 --> 09:58.840
Hey. Seen an ATF agent around here?

09:58.970 --> 10:00.430
Yeah, he went down below.

10:01.430 --> 10:02.520
How do I get there?

10:02.640 --> 10:04.480
The south side of the bridge.

10:12.400 --> 10:14.030
You Agent Minuti?

10:14.400 --> 10:16.150
Larry Minuti, ATF?

10:16.530 --> 10:18.990
No, Larry's my partner.
I'm Doug Carlin.

10:19.110 --> 10:20.910
Paul Pryzwarra, FBI.

10:21.280 --> 10:23.040
-How you doing?
-Where's Minuti?

10:23.330 --> 10:24.410
On vacation.

10:24.750 --> 10:28.080
Not anymore. We're calling in
half the region on this one.

10:28.620 --> 10:29.830
You can reach him?

10:30.000 --> 10:32.550
I tried. He's not picking up his phone.

10:34.630 --> 10:36.010
Well, try harder. It's important.

10:36.340 --> 10:37.630
Obviously.

10:39.010 --> 10:40.800
What are you looking for?

10:41.010 --> 10:42.890
Anything that doesn't belong.

10:46.430 --> 10:48.480
You want to give me a spot?

10:49.560 --> 10:50.810
Yeah.

11:04.120 --> 11:05.450
ANFO.

11:05.790 --> 11:07.500
Ammonium nitrate, water-soluble.

11:07.620 --> 11:10.250
Fuel oil would have burnt off
during the blast.

11:10.540 --> 11:11.000
Between the river and the rain,
if ANFO was used,

11:10.960 --> 11:12.540
Between the river and the rain,
if ANFO was used,

11:12.670 --> 11:13.840
the only place you'd find it would be...

11:13.960 --> 11:15.750
Underneath this bridge.

11:16.210 --> 11:17.670
That's right.

11:18.380 --> 11:20.510
We can't rule out an accident
at this point.

11:20.630 --> 11:22.850
-It's not officially a crime scene yet.
-Here's a thought.

11:22.970 --> 11:24.010
Why don't we double the perimeter

11:24.140 --> 11:25.930
so we don't have wall-to-wall trailers
down there?

11:26.060 --> 11:27.520
No, we're gonna need
all our manpower

11:27.640 --> 11:29.440
for evidence control
and witness processing.

11:29.560 --> 11:30.770
Now, we need to keep it tight

11:30.900 --> 11:33.190
until we can determine
that it is a crime investigation.

11:33.310 --> 11:35.020
It is a crime investigation.

11:35.150 --> 11:36.780
Got a piece of electric blasting cap

11:36.900 --> 11:38.780
and a strand
of what appears to be leg wire.

11:41.320 --> 11:44.660
About a million of those blue particles
washed up on the Algiers side.

11:44.780 --> 11:47.290
It's probably from
a plastic container or a barrel.

11:47.580 --> 11:48.620
ANFO?

11:48.750 --> 11:50.460
Most likely.
There was post-blast residue

11:50.580 --> 11:52.460
under the Crescent City Bridge.

11:52.580 --> 11:55.130
The insulation on the leg wire
will inform us

11:55.250 --> 11:57.590
of who the manufacturer
of the blasting cap is.

11:57.710 --> 11:59.300
Then we go after
the switching mechanism

11:59.420 --> 12:00.880
and the bomb's power source.

12:01.010 --> 12:03.930
We probably don't need to wait for
the lab to tell us what we already know,

12:04.050 --> 12:06.100
that this is an explosive and a trigger.

12:06.430 --> 12:07.680
And you are?

12:07.810 --> 12:10.060
Oh, I'm sorry. I'm Doug Carlin, ATF.

12:10.180 --> 12:11.810
-Who's in charge?
-We're working on that now.

12:11.940 --> 12:12.980
Gentlemen, please.

12:13.100 --> 12:14.980
Ed Elkins. I'm in charge.

12:15.110 --> 12:16.150
-Oh, good, good, good.
-Yeah.

12:16.270 --> 12:17.820
You're in charge, then? Okay.

12:18.110 --> 12:19.990
First things first.
Where's the coffeepot?

12:20.110 --> 12:21.150
Ed?

12:21.860 --> 12:24.070
Come on, this is a police investigation,
right? Operation.

12:24.200 --> 12:25.830
We gotta have a coffeepot.

12:25.950 --> 12:27.950
Yeah, you'll find it in the back.

12:28.080 --> 12:29.120
-Back there?
-Yeah.

12:29.250 --> 12:31.080
He is in charge. Thank you, gentlemen.

12:54.730 --> 12:56.020
See anything?

12:56.150 --> 12:57.440
Traffic.

12:57.570 --> 12:59.320
Hit rewind for me.

13:00.360 --> 13:01.400
Hey, did Larry call?

13:01.530 --> 13:03.490
Still not answering his cell.
We left another message.

13:03.610 --> 13:04.610
All right.

13:04.740 --> 13:06.870
-Say, that girl ever get ahold of you?
-What girl?

13:06.990 --> 13:09.450
You know, sexy voice, asked if
you were tall, dark and handsome.

13:09.580 --> 13:10.580
I gave her two out of three.

13:10.700 --> 13:12.200
Two out of three. That's very good.
Hit play.

13:12.330 --> 13:13.620
Thank you.

13:19.000 --> 13:20.500
Hey, Larry, this is Doug.
How you doing?

13:20.630 --> 13:22.470
Listen, I know you're maybe still
pissed off at me,

13:22.590 --> 13:24.220
but you need to
get your behind down here, all right?

13:24.340 --> 13:25.430
-Doug.
-Yeah?

13:25.550 --> 13:27.720
Doug, Orleans Parish on line one.
It's Sheriff Reed.

13:27.850 --> 13:30.060
They pulled a body out of the water,
and they want a profile.

13:30.180 --> 13:31.770
All right,
tell him they don't need a profile.

13:31.890 --> 13:34.730
-Just tell him to bag it. I'll call him back.
-Okay, got it.

13:36.770 --> 13:38.230
Put this on a candy wrapper?

13:38.360 --> 13:39.570
It's all I had.

13:39.690 --> 13:41.610
Cutting back, huh?

13:43.440 --> 13:45.200
Hold it right there.

13:47.030 --> 13:50.330
Yeah, this is ATF Agent Doug Carlin
returning your call.

13:50.450 --> 13:53.580
My cell number is 504-555-0130.

13:54.330 --> 13:55.500
What's that?

13:55.620 --> 13:57.040
Looks like a dude on a bike.

13:57.170 --> 13:59.250
Run it forward a little bit.

14:01.130 --> 14:02.590
Stop right there.

14:05.300 --> 14:07.260
What is he doing?

14:08.430 --> 14:10.260
Going to the bathroom?

14:14.640 --> 14:16.940
Run it forward, run it forward.

14:21.150 --> 14:23.730
-What time does it say?
-10:47.

14:23.860 --> 14:27.280
-That's before the explosion, isn't it?
-Right before.

14:29.820 --> 14:32.660
<i>Can I have your attention, please?</i>
<i>Thanks very much for coming-</i>

14:32.790 --> 14:36.910
<i>I'm Jack McCready, special agent</i>
<i>in charge of this investigation-</i>

14:37.500 --> 14:39.540
<i>First, let me say our hearts go out</i>

14:39.670 --> 14:42.040
<i>to all of those affected by this tragedy-</i>

14:44.170 --> 14:46.630
<i>Early estimates</i>
<i>place the number of casualties</i>

14:46.760 --> 14:50.720
<i>at 543 men, women and children-</i>

14:51.680 --> 14:54.390
<i>Now, Lord knows this city has seen</i>
<i>its share of pain,</i>

14:54.470 --> 14:56.230
<i>but unlike Katrina,</i>

14:56.890 --> 14:59.230
<i>this disaster was not an act of nature-</i>

15:00.520 --> 15:02.980
<i>After careful review of evidence</i>
<i>retrieved at the scene,</i>

15:03.110 --> 15:06.570
<i>we have concluded</i>
<i>this was a deliberate act of terrorism,</i>

15:07.360 --> 15:10.070
<i>and the President concurs</i>
<i>with our assessment-</i>

15:10.200 --> 15:12.780
<i>On our end,</i>
<i>we have to ask for your patience,</i>

15:12.910 --> 15:14.660
<i>as the investigation will take time-</i>

15:14.790 --> 15:18.500
<i>It's a unique and complicated</i>
<i>crime scene-</i>

15:18.620 --> 15:22.170
<i>There's no baggage checks-</i>
<i>There's no flight data recorder-</i>

15:22.590 --> 15:24.170
<i>There are maximum casualties,</i>

15:24.300 --> 15:27.970
<i>and most of the evidence</i>
<i>is under 100 feet of muddy water-</i>

15:29.550 --> 15:31.300
<i>There are no shortcuts-</i>

15:33.890 --> 15:35.890
-Kevin, where's Doug?
-You just missed him.

15:36.020 --> 15:38.140
-Well, his car's still here.
-Took the streetcar.

15:38.270 --> 15:40.480
-What? Streetcar?
-Hey, don't look at me.

15:40.900 --> 15:43.610
It's part of his process.
He says it helps him think.

15:49.240 --> 15:50.280
Sheriff Reed.

15:51.860 --> 15:53.870
How you doing?
It's Doug Carlin returning your call.

15:53.990 --> 15:56.330
Hey, Doug. I know you got
your hands full right now.

15:56.450 --> 15:58.660
Yeah, that's okay.
What do you got for me, Bob?

15:58.790 --> 16:00.750
Well, a couple of kids found a woman

16:00.870 --> 16:02.750
face down in the waters
off Algiers Point.

16:05.420 --> 16:08.170
Right, well, you're gonna see
a lot of that over the next few weeks.

16:08.300 --> 16:11.590
We've just set up ECC.
Just have Crime Scene bag it for us.

16:11.720 --> 16:14.260
<i>Well, we already done that-</i>
<i>The body's at the ME's right now-</i>

16:14.390 --> 16:15.600
Crime Scene's already been there?

16:15.720 --> 16:17.310
<i>Yeah, they've been and gone-</i>

16:17.430 --> 16:19.180
Well, exactly what time
did this woman wash up on shore?

16:22.600 --> 16:25.820
Kid called it in at 10:42 a.m.

16:27.020 --> 16:28.610
You mean 11:42, don't you?

16:28.730 --> 16:31.740
No, I mean 10:42.
I got the sheet right in front of me,

16:32.070 --> 16:34.370
and I got my reading glasses on.

16:38.870 --> 16:42.750
Immediately evident is the
focal charring of the limbs and torso.

16:44.290 --> 16:46.920
Anterior face, neck and chest
are intact,

16:48.340 --> 16:51.340
though swollen
from apparent immersion in water.

17:00.680 --> 17:01.600
Hold her hand for me, will you?
Right here.

17:01.560 --> 17:03.270
Hold her hand for me, will you?
Right here.

17:04.650 --> 17:06.020
There we go.

17:06.150 --> 17:08.860
Each digit of the right hand
has been severed

17:09.190 --> 17:11.280
between the middle
and distal phalanges. Thanks.

17:13.200 --> 17:16.280
Angle of shearing indicates
a single sharp-force trauma,

17:16.820 --> 17:18.620
possibly caused by shrapnel.

17:18.740 --> 17:22.200
No. No,
it's too even to be shrapnel trauma.

17:23.540 --> 17:26.460
Posterior charring
gives off a strong odour,

17:26.580 --> 17:29.550
suggesting perimortem immersion
in burning fuel.

17:30.500 --> 17:31.670
Diesel.

17:31.800 --> 17:33.760
-Accelerant, maybe?
-I don't know.

17:33.880 --> 17:37.430
If she was that close to the bomb, she
probably wouldn't be laying here now.

17:38.600 --> 17:39.930
What are you doing?

17:41.020 --> 17:42.730
What are you doing?

17:43.140 --> 17:44.310
You got a UV gun?

17:44.440 --> 17:46.190
Yeah, on the table behind you.

17:49.860 --> 17:52.070
-You see that?
-Duct tape.

17:54.700 --> 17:56.490
What's that stippling? You see that?

17:56.610 --> 17:59.490
Adhesive probably retained
some substance against the water.

17:59.620 --> 18:00.660
Yeah.

18:06.210 --> 18:07.250
Yeah, go ahead.

18:07.370 --> 18:09.340
I ran down those MPRs for you.

18:09.460 --> 18:12.590
A Claire Kuchever
was reported missing this morning.

18:12.710 --> 18:15.720
<i>Supposed to pick up her father</i>
<i>from the airport, pulled a no-show-</i>

18:15.840 --> 18:16.930
Okay.

18:18.550 --> 18:21.140
All right, Phil,
I want you to do a full autopsy.

18:21.760 --> 18:24.020
Concentrate on time and cause.

18:25.850 --> 18:27.690
Full spread of lab tests. Everything.

18:27.810 --> 18:31.020
Just pretend like the ferry explosion
never happened today, okay?

18:31.150 --> 18:32.480
Absolutely.

18:36.110 --> 18:37.280
Claire?

18:41.410 --> 18:44.040
-She's beautiful, huh?
-Yeah.

18:44.580 --> 18:45.660
Very.

19:17.360 --> 19:19.990
You'll need a photograph
for your investigation, right?

19:21.450 --> 19:24.410
There's plenty in the house.
Plenty to choose from.

19:27.410 --> 19:31.040
Mr Kuchever, I'm sorry about this,

19:34.300 --> 19:37.340
but I'm gonna need you
to confirm your daughter's identity.

19:43.260 --> 19:44.430
Okay.

19:45.260 --> 19:49.310
Now, anything that you can tell me

19:49.440 --> 19:52.440
about your daughter's activities
over the weekend,

19:52.560 --> 19:54.980
or any time, anything at all,
will be helpful.

19:55.610 --> 19:57.320
Well, I don't know.

19:57.440 --> 19:59.360
My flight got in
at 8:00 a.m. this morning,

19:59.490 --> 20:02.450
and she was supposed to pick me up,
but she wasn't there.

20:02.570 --> 20:04.450
I thought maybe she just overslept,

20:04.580 --> 20:07.620
so I took a cab
and I went straight to her house.

20:07.750 --> 20:09.290
Her and Alan's car was gone,

20:09.410 --> 20:12.290
so I thought
maybe she'd just finally sold it.

20:12.420 --> 20:14.340
-Who's Alan?
-Her fiancé.

20:14.590 --> 20:16.090
Or ex-fiancé.

20:16.460 --> 20:18.760
They broke up a few months ago.

20:19.090 --> 20:20.630
And where is he now, Alan?

20:20.760 --> 20:23.050
-He moved to Montreal.
-Okay.

20:24.140 --> 20:26.600
She was too good for him, anyway.

20:26.720 --> 20:29.270
I got a sweater that she left,
if you want to take it.

20:29.390 --> 20:33.940
No, that's okay. But if you have keys
to her house, I would appreciate it.

20:35.480 --> 20:37.650
Oh, she had a date.

20:38.110 --> 20:41.650
Last night on the phone, she told me
that she was gonna meet someone,

20:41.780 --> 20:45.030
but she didn't say who.
Her friend Beth set it up.

20:45.160 --> 20:46.240
Beth.

20:46.370 --> 20:50.160
Beth Walsh. Claire baby-sits
her daughter, Abbey, sometimes.

20:50.290 --> 20:51.370
Okay.

20:53.370 --> 20:54.670
Thank you.

20:55.330 --> 20:57.130
That's good for now.

20:59.340 --> 21:01.260
Somebody'll be in touch.

21:04.220 --> 21:05.720
Agent Carlin?

21:06.970 --> 21:08.010
Doug.

21:08.180 --> 21:10.180
I want you to take these.

21:11.270 --> 21:12.430
Well, that's...

21:12.560 --> 21:15.810
Just go through them
when you get a chance.

21:16.690 --> 21:19.400
-Well, it's really not necessary.
-Yes, it is.

21:19.860 --> 21:23.200
See, I know how these things go,
Agent Carlin,

21:23.400 --> 21:25.570
and I need her to matter to you.

23:18.600 --> 23:20.940
<i>Monday, 7:48 p-m-</i>

23:21.060 --> 23:22.770
<i>Hi, Claire- It's Dad-</i>

23:22.900 --> 23:25.190
<i>My flight gets in</i>
<i>at 7:55 tomorrow morning,</i>

23:25.320 --> 23:28.030
<i>so don't stay up too late-</i>
<i>Love you- Bye-bye-</i>

23:28.990 --> 23:31.910
<i>Tuesday, 9:44 a-m-</i>

23:32.030 --> 23:34.030
<i>Claire? Hi, it's Beth- Are you there?</i>

23:34.160 --> 23:35.200
<i>I'm sorry to call you so early,</i>

23:35.330 --> 23:37.080
<i>but you said you were gonna call me</i>
<i>when you got home,</i>

23:37.200 --> 23:38.580
<i>and when you didn't,</i>
<i>I started to get worried-</i>

23:38.710 --> 23:40.750
<i>-Beth, is this a joke?</i>
<i>-Oh, hey, hey! No-</i>

23:40.880 --> 23:42.750
<i>Like I said, I was just worried</i>
<i>about you, that's all-</i>

23:42.880 --> 23:45.000
<i>I can't talk right now-</i>
<i>Someone's here- I'll call you later-</i>

23:45.130 --> 23:46.460
<i>Claire---</i>

23:49.630 --> 23:51.970
<i>Tuesday, 9:50 a-m-</i>

23:57.060 --> 24:00.020
<i>Tuesday, 10:04 a-m-</i>

24:00.770 --> 24:04.770
<i>Claire, it's Dad- I did say 7:55, didn't I?</i>

24:04.900 --> 24:07.030
<i>I'm here at the airport, waiting for you-</i>

24:07.150 --> 24:10.240
<i>If you're not coming, I hope</i>
<i>you're sending Beth or someone-</i>

24:10.360 --> 24:11.910
<i>Call me-</i>

24:13.870 --> 24:16.490
<i>Tuesday, 1: 18 p-m-</i>

24:16.950 --> 24:20.210
<i>Yeah, this is A TF Agent Doug Carlin</i>
<i>returning your call-</i>

24:20.330 --> 24:23.420
<i>My cell number is 504-555-0130-</i>

24:34.140 --> 24:36.680
<i>Tuesday, 1: 18 p-m-</i>

24:37.640 --> 24:40.940
<i>Yeah, this is A TF Agent Doug Carlin</i>
<i>returning your call-</i>

24:41.060 --> 24:44.360
<i>My cell number is 504-555-0130-</i>

24:59.120 --> 25:02.210
The blast wave initiated here,
hit the bulkhead

25:02.500 --> 25:05.130
and propagated fore and aft
along the path of least resistance

25:05.250 --> 25:07.500
until it hits this access hatch.

25:07.630 --> 25:09.800
And that's where it gets really bad.

25:09.920 --> 25:10.920
<i>The blast wave continues</i>

25:11.050 --> 25:13.550
<i>into the engine room,</i>
<i>bursting the fuel tanks-</i>

25:13.680 --> 25:16.010
<i>This utility shaft here</i>
<i>acts like a chimney,</i>

25:16.140 --> 25:18.640
<i>draws the thermal components</i>
<i>into the engine room,</i>

25:18.760 --> 25:21.810
which ignites the fuel vapour,
causing a secondary explosion

25:21.930 --> 25:24.100
of far greater magnitude.

25:24.230 --> 25:27.570
Essentially, the initial device
turns the whole ferry into a bomb

25:27.690 --> 25:29.440
and detonates it.

25:29.690 --> 25:31.320
And so our early guess

25:31.440 --> 25:33.820
is that the bomb vehicle
was a minivan or SUV.

25:33.950 --> 25:36.820
-Possibly red or tan.
-Make and model?

25:36.950 --> 25:41.200
-Take weeks, maybe months.
-I got a partial on the licence plate.

25:43.210 --> 25:44.330
Shit.

25:44.460 --> 25:47.330
Check all the SUVs and minivans
that are registered in the state.

25:47.460 --> 25:48.960
Anything recently rented or purchased,

25:49.090 --> 25:51.550
anything tied to a theft
or a missing persons report.

25:51.670 --> 25:52.920
-Agent McCready?
-Yeah.

25:53.050 --> 25:54.680
Doug Carlin, ATF.

25:55.680 --> 25:57.510
Oh, yeah. Oklahoma City.

25:57.800 --> 25:59.560
Right. That's right.

25:59.760 --> 26:01.680
This afternoon, I witnessed an autopsy

26:01.810 --> 26:04.520
of a young woman who washed up
off the Poland Wharf.

26:05.730 --> 26:09.060
Heavy fuel burns,
traces of PETN on her face.

26:09.190 --> 26:12.360
PETN, that's the base explosive
used by domestic terrorists.

26:12.900 --> 26:17.030
She also lost several fingers
in what appeared to be blast damage.

26:17.530 --> 26:18.530
Appeared?

26:18.660 --> 26:21.540
That's right. I checked the tide tables
against the position of the blast.

26:21.660 --> 26:24.210
For her to have washed up
that early and that far upriver,

26:24.330 --> 26:27.790
she would've had to have been killed
two hours before the ferry exploded.

26:27.920 --> 26:29.130
Before?

26:31.090 --> 26:32.920
She died before the explosion?

26:33.050 --> 26:36.760
She died before the explosion, yeah.
Her name is Claire Kuchever.

26:36.880 --> 26:40.050
She washed up before the explosion
and against the tide.

26:40.600 --> 26:43.220
-Do you have a scenario?
-Yes, I do.

26:43.350 --> 26:47.060
I believe that somebody abducted her
in her home, taped her mouth,

26:47.190 --> 26:49.980
bound her wrists, burnt her alive,
dumped her in the river

26:50.110 --> 26:53.110
so she would appear to be
just another disaster victim.

26:54.110 --> 26:55.690
A disaster that hadn't happened yet.

26:55.820 --> 26:58.360
But the PETN tells us

26:58.490 --> 27:01.120
that the bomber came in direct contact
with the victim.

27:01.240 --> 27:03.240
You solve her case,
you solve this case.

27:04.080 --> 27:05.580
Why this woman?

27:05.750 --> 27:08.330
Good question. Her SUV is missing.

27:09.630 --> 27:12.210
It's a tan and red Bronco.

27:12.340 --> 27:15.920
It could have been stolen
to drive the bomb to the ferry.

27:16.380 --> 27:17.510
Oh, one more thing.

27:17.630 --> 27:20.510
The victim called the local ATF office

27:20.640 --> 27:22.930
the morning of the explosion.

27:23.810 --> 27:24.890
Yeah.

27:25.980 --> 27:27.940
-We'll look into it.
-Okay.

27:29.150 --> 27:30.770
All right.

27:31.310 --> 27:32.400
Okay.

27:42.320 --> 27:43.780
Where's Larry?

27:44.200 --> 27:46.160
-What?
-Larry Minuti, my partner.

27:46.290 --> 27:48.710
That's his car right there. Is he here?

27:49.620 --> 27:52.080
I thought you said he was on vacation.

27:52.210 --> 27:54.040
Yeah, that's right.

27:56.840 --> 27:57.880
What?

28:01.300 --> 28:04.680
Those cars were brought here
from the Algiers ferry parking lot.

28:05.430 --> 28:08.640
They're the vehicles
that belonged to the victims.

28:23.240 --> 28:24.830
Sorry.

28:39.840 --> 28:41.180
So he's a former Marine?

28:41.300 --> 28:44.890
Yes, sir. Yeah. Local, too.
He's born and bred in New Orleans.

28:45.810 --> 28:47.010
His family still in the area?

28:47.140 --> 28:49.770
Nope. Nothing, really, but his job.

28:50.350 --> 28:52.520
-You like him?
-He's smart.

28:53.020 --> 28:54.690
Yeah, I like him, too.

28:54.810 --> 28:56.400
All right. Let's go find him.

29:22.630 --> 29:24.090
Oklahoma City.

29:27.640 --> 29:28.720
Yeah.

29:32.770 --> 29:35.060
-You and Larry were close?
-Yeah.

29:35.900 --> 29:39.900
Yeah, you know, close enough
to get on each other's nerves.

29:40.610 --> 29:44.740
Doug, I've been put in charge
of a newly-formed investigative unit.

29:44.990 --> 29:48.740
The ferry disaster is our first case,
and I want you on the team.

29:48.870 --> 29:50.040
Why me?

29:50.540 --> 29:53.290
We've got
some unique time constraints.

29:53.410 --> 29:57.460
I need someone who can look
at a crime scene exactly one time,

29:57.880 --> 30:00.880
tell us what's missing,
tell us what shouldn't be there,

30:01.130 --> 30:02.420
tell us what we can ignore

30:02.550 --> 30:04.930
and, especially,
what we need to pursue.

30:05.050 --> 30:08.430
Also, you're local. You know the people
and you know the area.

30:08.550 --> 30:10.390
But why an ATF guy?

30:10.510 --> 30:12.980
Why not? It's your shot.

30:13.100 --> 30:15.810
You want to find the guy
who killed Minuti, don't you?

30:18.650 --> 30:19.690
Yes, I do.

30:43.050 --> 30:45.300
I guess you've got some questions.

30:45.420 --> 30:49.140
For me to have questions,
first I'd need to know something.

31:17.500 --> 31:19.040
Now I do have some questions.

31:19.170 --> 31:21.710
Don't touch anything.
We don't need you yet.

31:21.840 --> 31:24.670
Doug, you remember
Dr Alexander Denny.

31:25.590 --> 31:26.920
Where's my audio?

31:27.050 --> 31:29.760
Compensating for audio delay.
Just a second.

31:31.220 --> 31:33.600
Compensating for a technical blunder
by a tech guy...

31:33.720 --> 31:37.480
Solid stream. Minus four days,
six hours, three minutes, 45 seconds.

31:37.730 --> 31:39.940
And 14 and a half nanoseconds.

31:40.730 --> 31:41.770
Okay.

31:42.650 --> 31:45.690
Anytime you want to jump in here,
be my guest.

31:46.070 --> 31:47.240
-Me?
-Yeah.

31:56.910 --> 31:58.210
What are we looking for?

31:58.330 --> 32:01.540
You know, clues, suspects,
anything out of the norm.

32:02.380 --> 32:04.550
-When was this taken?
-Four and a half days ago.

32:04.670 --> 32:06.960
Gunnars,
try the guy with the backpack.

32:14.260 --> 32:15.720
Oh, that's tender.

32:16.060 --> 32:18.310
I wish I had someone. Okay, widen out.

32:18.430 --> 32:21.560
Let's cruise the car deck for a while,
see what we got.

32:26.530 --> 32:27.690
How can you change the angle

32:27.820 --> 32:30.070
on footage
taken four and a half days ago?

32:30.200 --> 32:31.490
This is a digital recreation.

32:31.610 --> 32:34.700
We're combining all the data we've got
into one fluid shot.

32:34.830 --> 32:37.240
Any angle, any view
within the target area.

32:39.290 --> 32:41.290
Okay, let's cruise the breezeway,

32:41.420 --> 32:43.540
see what we get there.

32:43.960 --> 32:46.250
It's a brand-new programme.
It's called Snow White.

32:46.380 --> 32:48.590
Our primary data comes from
seven orbiting satellites,

32:48.710 --> 32:52.260
but at any given time, as many as four
are surveilling one area.

32:52.430 --> 32:56.760
It's like having multiple eyewitnesses,
each with their own vantage point.

32:57.140 --> 32:58.600
Snow White?

33:03.310 --> 33:04.980
Well, which one of the seven dwarfs

33:05.110 --> 33:07.820
can explain to me
how you get the audio?

33:12.950 --> 33:14.660
I don't understand.

33:16.080 --> 33:17.540
Why do you gotta
look at four days ago?

33:17.660 --> 33:20.500
Why don't you just fast-forward it
to the day of the explosion?

33:20.620 --> 33:22.370
We have to wait.
It takes four and a half days

33:22.500 --> 33:24.500
to render this single fluid shot.

33:24.920 --> 33:26.250
The only thing that matters

33:26.380 --> 33:29.630
is that we have exactly one look
at any one time.

33:30.630 --> 33:33.340
Yeah. We can't go back 10 minutes,
you know?

33:33.470 --> 33:36.470
Can't look back and see
if there was a second gunman.

33:36.600 --> 33:40.930
We can't watch the agent
buying 10 pairs of cargo pants in 1983.

33:42.140 --> 33:43.980
All right? But given enough lead time,

33:44.100 --> 33:46.310
we can look anywhere
within the target area, all right?

33:46.440 --> 33:50.320
It's the when that's always constant.
It's always four days and six hours ago.

33:50.440 --> 33:51.900
Always. You understand?

33:52.030 --> 33:56.320
It's like a single trailing moment of now,
in the past.

33:57.580 --> 34:02.540
Okay. So if you can't move forward
or backward in time,

34:02.660 --> 34:04.620
how is it
the image keeps speeding up like that?

34:04.750 --> 34:07.960
It's not the image that's moving faster,
it's just our shifting point of view.

34:08.090 --> 34:10.840
The passage of time remains constant,
but we can shift our point of view

34:10.960 --> 34:13.170
within the data stream
as fast as we want.

34:13.550 --> 34:17.010
-You understand?
-Yeah. Yeah. No.

34:17.220 --> 34:18.350
Yeah, I know.

34:18.470 --> 34:20.640
So four days from...
Well, actually, three days from now,

34:20.760 --> 34:24.020
since it's after midnight,
you'll be able to look back

34:24.190 --> 34:25.850
to the day of the explosion,
see who did it,

34:25.980 --> 34:27.980
how they did it
and what they did it with.

34:28.110 --> 34:29.190
Yeah, you got it.

34:29.320 --> 34:31.360
The only thing is,
you need to tell us where to look,

34:31.480 --> 34:34.700
'cause, you know, we could miss it.

34:35.490 --> 34:38.490
Besides, three days could be too late.
He could leave the country,

34:38.620 --> 34:40.030
could strike again.

34:40.160 --> 34:42.450
We need to do whatever we can now.

34:42.580 --> 34:44.960
We know he's out there planning this.

34:45.080 --> 34:47.170
We just don't know where to look.

34:48.580 --> 34:51.050
So, Agent Carlin, where do we look?

34:55.590 --> 34:57.470
Claire Kuchever's house.

34:59.890 --> 35:01.810
Address is in range.

35:01.970 --> 35:04.430
All right, match the viewer settings
to the signal.

35:08.560 --> 35:11.150
-Signal's solid.
-All right, dazzle me.

35:26.290 --> 35:27.370
What?

35:27.500 --> 35:29.920
You see, with Snow White
we can track through walls.

35:30.790 --> 35:32.750
It's part of the same infrared
thermal-imaging stuff

35:32.880 --> 35:33.920
they're using in Iraq.

35:34.050 --> 35:37.840
<i>-Hello- This is 877-504-8423-</i>
-We triangulate from four satellites,

35:37.970 --> 35:39.930
pick up the heat signal and reconstruct.

35:40.050 --> 35:42.220
Basically, we can walk through walls.

35:44.390 --> 35:46.060
Claire Kuchever.

35:46.180 --> 35:48.440
<i>-Claire? Hello?</i>
-Did you know her?

35:48.980 --> 35:51.610
We held hands once,
but no, I didn't know her.

35:51.730 --> 35:53.940
<i>Just checking in,</i>
<i>wondering how you're doing-</i>

35:54.730 --> 35:57.780
<i>Montreal's fantastic,</i>
<i>but my boss is an ass-</i>

35:57.900 --> 36:00.070
Can you rotate the view,
see what she's looking at?

36:00.200 --> 36:01.370
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

36:01.490 --> 36:02.830
<i>I want you to come visit, though-</i>

36:02.950 --> 36:05.120
<i>The city's phenomenal-</i>
<i>You're gonna love it-</i>

36:05.240 --> 36:07.200
<i>Claire? Claire?</i>

36:07.330 --> 36:09.290
555-0118.

36:09.420 --> 36:10.790
-Somebody got that?
-Yeah.

36:10.920 --> 36:12.460
<i>Claire, you there?</i>

36:13.420 --> 36:16.510
<i>Listen, I've had a lot of time to think,</i>

36:23.850 --> 36:26.560
<i>and I need you to sell the Bronco</i>
<i>as soon as possible-</i>

36:31.730 --> 36:35.320
<i>Or at least pay me back my half-</i>
<i>I just really need the money-</i>

36:35.820 --> 36:37.820
<i>I love you, honey- Call me-</i>

36:38.360 --> 36:39.650
<i>Unbelievable-</i>

36:41.820 --> 36:44.530
-Where's she... Can you follow her?
-No problem.

37:01.680 --> 37:03.720
Yeah, I'm coming, I'm coming.

37:05.850 --> 37:06.850
What?

37:07.390 --> 37:11.230
It's Stalhuth, at that house you found.
Female murder victim, Claire?

37:14.020 --> 37:15.650
Right. What do you got?

37:15.770 --> 37:19.740
We got some bloody cotton swabs
and gauze strips in the bathroom,

37:19.860 --> 37:22.700
<i>some blood in the sink trap-</i>
<i>And, oh, hey, Carlin?</i>

37:22.820 --> 37:26.120
Man, when did you completely forget
how to investigate a crime scene?

37:26.240 --> 37:27.410
What do you mean?

37:27.540 --> 37:29.040
This place is lousy
with your fingerprints.

37:29.160 --> 37:31.040
They're all over the place.

37:37.420 --> 37:40.760
Do me a favour. Just describe what
you see for me, okay? Just humour me.

37:42.470 --> 37:45.010
Woman's bedroom. Vanity mirror.

37:45.930 --> 37:48.850
Dressing table with makeup,
knick-knacks.

37:48.970 --> 37:50.100
Okay, okay, okay, I get it.

37:50.220 --> 37:52.940
Is there anybody there?
Anybody brushing their teeth?

37:53.190 --> 37:57.730
No. Just a couple agents,
including Hendricks, who's bent over,

37:57.860 --> 38:00.610
and I have a fine view
of the crack of his ass.

38:00.730 --> 38:03.610
Okay, I get the picture.
Talk to you later.

38:04.030 --> 38:05.490
You satisfied?

38:05.990 --> 38:08.280
She was supposed to go on a date
the night before she died.

38:08.410 --> 38:11.200
I want to get her appointment books
and everything brought down here,

38:11.330 --> 38:14.830
you know, her phone records,
credit cards, diaries, anything.

38:14.960 --> 38:16.960
I wanna know everything
there is to know about this woman.

38:17.080 --> 38:19.170
Well, shouldn't we
be concentrating on the ferry?

38:19.300 --> 38:21.630
Well, yeah, it's likely that our guy

38:21.760 --> 38:25.800
cased the ferry first,
but we don't know when.

38:26.510 --> 38:27.970
We don't even know what he looks like.

38:28.100 --> 38:31.140
I mean, we could stare him
right in the face and not know it's him.

38:31.270 --> 38:34.230
But we will notice a change,
even a small change, in her life.

38:40.020 --> 38:41.230
<i>-Hey, Beth-</i>
<i>-Claire-</i>

38:41.360 --> 38:43.990
<i>That guy I've been telling you about</i>
<i>really wants to meet you-</i>

38:44.110 --> 38:46.320
<i>Okay- Tell him</i>
<i>I'll meet him Monday night-</i>

38:46.450 --> 38:47.450
Monday.

38:47.570 --> 38:48.990
<i>How about Sunday</i>
<i>if you're not doing anything?</i>

38:49.120 --> 38:50.740
<i>-No, Monday-</i>
<i>-Great- I'll give him your number-</i>

38:50.870 --> 38:52.870
<i>No, do not give him my number-</i>
<i>I'll go meet him-</i>

38:53.000 --> 38:54.620
<i>-He's not some psycho killer-</i>
-Who? Him who?

38:54.750 --> 38:58.000
<i>I don't even know if I can do it Monday-</i>
<i>Hang on-</i>

38:58.130 --> 38:59.670
Show me the book.

39:01.840 --> 39:02.920
<i>Monday works-</i>

39:03.050 --> 39:04.050
-Damn!
-Shit!

39:04.170 --> 39:05.220
Can we go back?

39:05.340 --> 39:06.380
-No.
-Seriously?

39:06.510 --> 39:09.010
No, it's far too much data
for any existing storage system.

39:09.140 --> 39:11.970
It's a constant stream.
There's no rewind, no second chances.

39:12.100 --> 39:13.930
We can record what we're seeing,
but we can't go back

39:14.060 --> 39:15.230
and choose to look
at something different.

39:15.350 --> 39:17.520
Okay. You said we can record, though?

39:17.650 --> 39:18.810
-Yes.
-Okay.

39:22.900 --> 39:26.950
Tell me, is there any scientific
or forensic insight likely to be gained

39:27.530 --> 39:30.120
by spying on this woman
in the shower?

39:30.240 --> 39:33.540
Shanti, we're trying to make sure
the woman's clean.

39:35.580 --> 39:37.410
All right, why don't you,

39:37.580 --> 39:40.710
you know, look around the rest of
the bathroom? Can you do that?

39:49.430 --> 39:51.600
-Gunnars.
-Yeah.

39:51.720 --> 39:52.760
-You back?
-Sorry.

39:52.890 --> 39:53.970
All right.

39:57.600 --> 39:59.440
Icy Hot, Band-Aids, baby oil.

39:59.600 --> 40:00.900
This woman needs a vice.

40:01.020 --> 40:02.570
What's on the other side of that wall?

40:02.690 --> 40:03.900
Kitchen.

40:04.070 --> 40:05.900
Let's take a look.

40:06.780 --> 40:09.610
<i>Hello? Hello?</i>

40:18.210 --> 40:21.170
Maybe there's someone out there.
Maybe there's a stalker.

40:21.290 --> 40:22.750
<i>Someone there?</i>

40:24.500 --> 40:26.010
<i>Hey, Ginger-</i>

40:30.430 --> 40:31.550
<i>Hello?</i>

40:33.640 --> 40:35.850
Does she know I'm here?
Does she know we're here?

40:35.970 --> 40:38.350
No, impossible. Strictly one-way.

40:40.190 --> 40:41.440
You sure?

40:52.660 --> 40:53.780
<i>Hello?</i>

40:53.910 --> 40:56.790
Okay, let's check the perimeter.

41:03.500 --> 41:04.670
Nobody.

41:07.090 --> 41:08.800
Who's watching her?

41:09.970 --> 41:11.130
We are.

41:43.580 --> 41:46.920
<i>They will also take up a request</i>
<i>for more money for the---</i>

41:51.380 --> 41:54.720
<i>God, thank you for blessing me</i>
<i>with this food and with my life-</i>

41:56.510 --> 41:59.970
<i>I know today's gonna be a great day-</i>
<i>Amen-</i>

42:04.770 --> 42:07.860
<i>You guys singing?</i>
<i>You singing a love song?</i>

42:09.070 --> 42:11.690
<i>You singing a love song</i>
<i>to one another?</i>

42:12.740 --> 42:14.200
<i>What you doing?</i>

42:37.140 --> 42:38.140
<i>Hi-</i>

42:46.270 --> 42:48.860
<i>Yeah, it's been a while-</i>

42:58.280 --> 43:01.410
Everything God has done
will remain forever.

43:01.950 --> 43:03.830
There is nothing to add to it,

43:03.950 --> 43:05.830
nothing to take from it.

43:06.080 --> 43:08.960
God has done this
so that men should be in awe...

43:09.080 --> 43:10.590
Ex didn't show.

43:10.710 --> 43:13.880
-Would you?
-Whatever is has already been,

43:14.010 --> 43:16.260
and what will be has been before.

43:17.090 --> 43:20.100
God calls forth the past.

43:26.690 --> 43:28.400
Claire loved music.

43:29.150 --> 43:30.860
There's a church near our house,

43:31.730 --> 43:34.110
and gospel fills the neighbourhood.

43:35.110 --> 43:39.700
When she was little,
Claire saw a jazz funeral procession.

43:40.620 --> 43:42.330
She asked me that day,

43:42.490 --> 43:44.950
"Why do they always wait until the end

43:45.370 --> 43:47.080
"to play the good music?"

43:47.540 --> 43:50.330
Claire, honey, the music's playing
for you now and forever.

44:13.150 --> 44:15.190
Were there four limo drivers or five?

44:15.320 --> 44:18.400
Four limos.
Must have been four drivers, right?

44:21.120 --> 44:22.490
He was here.

44:27.620 --> 44:29.580
Address is in range.

44:31.250 --> 44:32.630
Palace Restaurant.

44:32.750 --> 44:34.800
They got good food there.

44:39.010 --> 44:40.760
<i>I'm so sorry for the wait- I really am-</i>

44:40.890 --> 44:41.930
<i>Listen---</i>

44:42.050 --> 44:43.800
<i>Your table will be ready</i>
<i>in a few minutes-</i>

44:43.930 --> 44:45.350
<i>Drinks are on me, all right?</i>

44:45.470 --> 44:47.430
<i>It is gonna be a few more minutes</i>
<i>for your table---</i>

44:47.560 --> 44:49.350
<i>Go upstairs and see if Table 45</i>
<i>is ready for desserts-</i>

44:49.480 --> 44:50.480
<i>-All right?</i>
<i>-I will-</i>

44:50.600 --> 44:53.310
<i>Hold on- Hang on- Hello? Hello?</i>

44:53.440 --> 44:55.520
<i>Hey, are you the lady</i>
<i>with the Bronco for sale?</i>

44:55.650 --> 44:57.030
-That's him.
-How do you know?

44:57.150 --> 44:59.030
-That's him.
-Well, call up the phone list.

44:59.150 --> 45:01.200
Let's see if it's a number we've tracked.

45:02.740 --> 45:04.740
<i>Yes, that's me- Just a second-</i>

45:04.950 --> 45:06.040
<i>Cover for me, all right?</i>

45:06.160 --> 45:07.580
Keep that tape running, too.

45:07.700 --> 45:10.410
I'm gonna want a recording
of this conversation for voice analysis.

45:10.540 --> 45:12.500
<i>-I'm here- Can you hear me?</i>
<i>-Well, hello, there-</i>

45:12.630 --> 45:14.040
<i>Let me tell you, first off,</i>

45:14.170 --> 45:16.250
<i>I'm what you could call</i>
<i>a real motivated buyer-</i>

45:16.380 --> 45:17.380
I bet you are.

45:17.510 --> 45:18.920
<i>I'm ready to get something right away-</i>

45:19.050 --> 45:21.550
<i>That sounds great-</i>
<i>I need to sell something right away-</i>

45:21.680 --> 45:24.890
<i>Your price looks good,</i>
<i>model, mileage---</i>

45:25.300 --> 45:27.140
<i>So where can I come by and see it?</i>

45:27.260 --> 45:28.720
Don't tell him.

45:28.850 --> 45:31.560
<i>I'm at 827 Kings Oak,</i>
<i>in the French Quarter-</i>

45:31.640 --> 45:33.440
<i>-Need directions?</i>
-Now he knows where she lives.

45:33.560 --> 45:36.400
<i>No, no, I'll find you-</i>
<i>Is tomorrow night good?</i>

45:36.520 --> 45:39.320
<i>Actually, l---</i>
<i>Tomorrow night is not good-</i>

45:39.440 --> 45:40.780
-Tomorrow?
<i>-I'm going out tomorrow-</i>

45:40.900 --> 45:43.280
He wants to wait for the last
possible moment to steal her car,

45:43.410 --> 45:45.160
then it's too late to report it.

45:45.280 --> 45:46.450
<i>How does Tuesday sound?</i>

45:46.580 --> 45:49.750
Got it. 504-555-0147.

45:49.910 --> 45:51.210
I see it. Tracking.

45:51.330 --> 45:53.170
<i>I think that's gonna be too late-</i>

45:53.290 --> 45:55.080
<i>See, I need the vehicle</i>
<i>Tuesday morning-</i>

45:55.210 --> 45:57.840
<i>Is there anyone else there</i>
<i>that can show me the car?</i>

45:57.960 --> 45:59.630
<i>-No- Sorry-</i>
-He's thinking.

45:59.760 --> 46:01.260
<i>I'll tell you what- There's a K5 Blazer---</i>

46:01.380 --> 46:03.130
A date means
somebody's gonna be expecting her

46:03.260 --> 46:04.800
and will miss her
if she doesn't show up.

46:04.930 --> 46:07.100
That could ruin his plans.
